To align a row of divs to the right using flex in CSS, you can use the `justify-content` property and set it to `flex-end`. Here's an example:
```
.container {
  display: flex;
  justify-content: flex-end;
}

.item {
  width: 100px;
  height: 50px;
  margin: 10px;
  background-color: #eee;
}
```
In this example, the `.container` element is set to `display: flex`, which enables flexbox layout. The `justify-content` property is then set to `flex-end`, which aligns the items to the right of the container. Finally, each item in the row (represented by the `.item` class) has a fixed width and height, as well as some margin for spacing between them.

You can also use `margin-left: auto;` on the last element in the row to push it to the right.
```
.container {
  display: flex;
}

.item {
  width: 100px;
  height: 50px;
  margin: 10px;
  background-color: #eee;
}

.item:last-child {
  margin-left: auto;
}
```
This will push the last item in the row to the right, without affecting the position of the other items.
